SIMPLE: raffish
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Raffish
<hw>Raff"ish</hw> <pr>(r⟦adot⟧f"⟦icr⟧sh)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<def>Resembling, or having the character of, raff, or a raff; worthless;
low.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A sad, <qex>raffish</qex>, disreputable character.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Mildly disreputable; disregarding conventional
morality; charmingly dissolute{3} or nonconformist.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tales of his [Ted Kennedy's] drinking and <qex>raffish</qex>
behavior have become part of his public persona, often lumped under a
vaster damnation known as ⟦ldquo⟧the character issue⟦rdquo⟧.⟦br⟧
. . .⟦br⟧
He appears to compartmentalize his off-duty conduct and his Senate
responsibilities; during dozens of interviews for this article, with
friends and foes, not one could cite an instance in which drinking
appeared to impair him professionally. His adversaries grumble about it
anyway; friends portray it as relatively harmless and charming.⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<person>Orrin Hatch</person>, the conservative Utah Republican who is
also a Mormon, tells this story with what he describes as ⟦ldquo⟧a
tremendous brotherly affection.⟦rdquo⟧ Two days before the Senate
adjourned in October 1988, <persfn>Hatch</persfn> took a call from
<person>Frank Madsen</person>, a former aide who had moved to
<city>Boston</city> to supervise 200 young Mormon missionaries. Would
<persfn>Hatch</persfn> come speak to them? Would he bring
<persfn>Kennedy</persfn>? Would he ask <persfn>Kennedy</persfn> to
reserve Faneuil Hall for the event?⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
With some misgivings, Hatch agreed to try. Shortly before midnight, he
found <persfn>Kennedy</persfn> and <person>Chris Dodd</person> in the
Capitol. Neither was feeling any pain.⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
⟦ldquo⟧Ted, I've got a favor to ask.⟦rdquo⟧⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
Kennedy wrapped an arm around Hatch. ⟦ldquo⟧Done!⟦rdquo⟧⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
Hatch held up a restraining hand. ⟦ldquo⟧No, hear me out. You remember
my aide, Frank Madsen -- ⟦rdquo⟧⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
⟦ldquo⟧Great fellow! Great fellow!⟦rdquo⟧⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
⟦ldquo⟧He's now in Boston -- ⟦rdquo⟧⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
⟦ldquo⟧My home town! My home town!⟦rdquo⟧⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<persfn>Hatch</persfn> eventually made his request.
<persfn>Kennedy</persfn> assented. Hatch returned to his office, typed
out the agreement and sent it to Kennedy's office. The next day, Hatch
spied Kennedy reading the memo. ⟦ldquo⟧Orrin,⟦rdquo⟧ Kennedy called in
mock horror, ⟦ldquo⟧what else did I agree to?⟦rdquo⟧ Three months later,
in January 1989, Hatch and Kennedy stood elbow-to-elbow in Faneuil Hall,
addressing the Mormon missionaries.</q> <qau>Rick Atkinson, Washington
Post, Sept. 29, 1990</qau>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Dissolute; rakish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q> Of all such places, <city>Santa Fe</city> may well be the least
<qex>raffish</qex>. At least in the off-season, it's a town that goes to
bed early, showing all the prudent reserve of a city of bankers and
claims adjusters. In the historic center, a visitor searches in vain for
tawdry traces of the hard-drinking, wild-womanizing, heavy-gambling
cowboy town this once must have been.</q> <qau>Brad Leithauser
(⟦ldquo⟧Santa Fe⟦rdquo⟧, in New York Times Magazine / May 13,
2001).</qau>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q> Over the years, it [Macau] has maintained a downright
<qex>raffish</qex> atmosphere, complete with warring gangsters.</q>
<qau>Yvette Ziols.</qau>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Vulgarly gaudy; cheap and tawdry; <as>as, a tendency
toward gaudy jewelry, bright colors and generally <ex>raffish</ex>
dress</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q> A lonely orphan, Lilli, lands a job with a <qex>raffish</qex> and
run-down carnival. The wide-eyed and innocent orphan is mesmerized by
its gritty, tawdry glamour.</q> <qau>Anonymous review of the play
<i>Carnival</i>
(https://web.archive.org/web/20040904064952/http://www.kt-online.org/plays/02-carnival-frame.html)</qau>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Appealing to or frequented by dissolute or
disreputable people; <as>as, a <ex>raffish</ex> night
club</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Raffle</ent>⟦br⟧
